<div id="5-fantastic-marketing-podcasts"></div>
<h2>5 of the best marketing podcasts, according to the pros</h2>
<p>I‚Äôm impressed with the variety of podcasts people proposed. There are quick listens for bite-sized takeaways on specific tactics and deep dives into big topics that are shaping marketing right now.</p>
<div id="seo-office-hours"></div>
<h3>1. SEO office hours</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.goodsignals.com/seo-office-hours/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">SEO Office Hours</a> is a weekly, one-hour podcast that brings together some of the smartest <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/seo">search engine optimization</a> pros in the business. But what‚Äôs really cool is that it‚Äôs a Q&amp;A format recorded live from Zoom, complete with an audience full of the questions we all have about <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/07/06/how-to-rank-higher-on-google">getting found through search</a>.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-office-hours.webp" alt="Best marketing podcasts - SEO office hours." width="937" height="459" class="aligncenter wp-image-93769 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-office-hours.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-office-hours-480x235.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.goodsignals.com/seo-office-hours/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>If a live Q&amp;A chat about SEO reminds you of John Mueller‚Äôs old Webmaster Hangouts, that‚Äôs intentional. ‚ÄúWhen John stopped, I didn‚Äôt want that resource to disappear,‚Äù said <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/michaelchidzey/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Michael Chidzey</a>, co-host of SEO Office Hours and CEO of <a href="https://www.goodsignals.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Good Signals</a>. ‚ÄúI reached out and asked if he‚Äôd be okay with me giving it a go, and he‚Äôs been incredibly supportive ever since.‚Äù</p>
<p>Michael tuned into Mueller‚Äôs sessions religiously. ‚ÄúThey weren‚Äôt just Q&amp;A sessions. They were a lifeline for anyone struggling with a traffic drop, wanting to sound out a new idea, or discussing some sort of change or update.‚Äù</p>
<p>With Mueller‚Äôs blessing, he worked to create a similarly supportive atmosphere, but with a collaborative mindset. ‚ÄúOf course, I‚Äôm not John Mueller from Google, so I built the show in my own way,‚Äù Michael told me. ‚ÄúI invited special guests to bring their perspectives. The first was a good friend of mine, Jo Juliana Turnbull. She was so good that I asked her to come back as a regular host. From there, we evolved into a panel format with me, Jo, and two rotating guests.‚Äù</p>
<p>For Michael‚Äôs co-host, Jo, it‚Äôs the lack of barriers that makes the show special. ‚ÄúWe welcome first-time speakers, we answer all<a href="https://localiq.com/blog/2025-local-seo-trends/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> SEO questions</a>, there is no such thing as a silly question,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúPeople feel welcome, and we have a regular group of attendees from all over the world.‚Äù</p>
<p>The live format plays a big role in the podcast, since it lets the audience run the show. ‚ÄúAs a host, I‚Äôm constantly watching the audience‚Äôs expressions: puzzled looks, nods of agreement, those moments of real engagement,‚Äù Michael said. ‚ÄúThat dictates whether we dig deeper into a topic, clarify something, or swiftly move on to the next question.‚Äù</p>
<p>‚ÄúToday, SEO Office Hours feels less like a podcast and more like a weekly gathering of some of the smartest, most generous people in the industry,‚Äù Michael added. ‚ÄúAnd honestly, even if I weren‚Äôt running it, I‚Äôd still be there every Friday.‚Äù</p>
<h4>One big takeaway</h4>
<p>The lesson for Michael is that consistency wins the day. ‚ÄúWhen we started SEO Office Hours, I set a target: every Friday for three months, no matter what,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúWithout that commitment, it would have been easy to stop after the first or second episode. But when giving up isn‚Äôt an option, you focus on making it better and better‚Äîand on optimizing your time to keep it going.‚Äù</p>
<p>‚ÄúI think that mindset applies to everything in marketing: whether it‚Äôs launching a newsletter, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/social-media-strategy">building a social presence</a>, or implementing a content strategy. Consistency compounds. The longer you stick with it, the more valuable it becomes.‚Äù</p>
<h4>The past episode to have in your playlist</h4>
<p>Michael said they‚Äôve begun rotating in occasional co-hosts, and that‚Äôs expanded the show‚Äôs ability to deliver diverse ideas. ‚ÄúOne of my <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A4qHN3pqZtU" target="_blank" rel="noopener">favorite episodes</a> was when I sat in the audience myself and Yordan Dimitrov co-hosted with Jo,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúIt was amazing to experience the show from the audience‚Äôs perspective and see just how valuable‚Äîand fun‚Äîit is when you‚Äôre on the other side.‚Äù</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f6d1.png" alt="üõë" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Podcasts help get more people to your website.</strong> Download <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/increase-traffic-to-your-website?cid=Web_Any_BlogInContent_PPC_25WaysIncreaseTraffic_Download">25 Ways to Increase Traffic to Your Website</a> for even more.</p>
<div id="market-movers-building-brands-and-links-with-linkifi"></div>
<h3>2. Market Movers: Building Brands &amp; Links with Linkifi</h3>
<p>There‚Äôs nothing niche about <a href="https://www.marketmoverspod.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Market Movers: Building Brands &amp; Links</a>. Each week, the show‚Äôs co-hosts (and <a href="https://www.linkifi.io/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Linkifi</a> co-founders) <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/chris-panteli/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Christopher Panteli</a> and Nick Biggs invite guests with wildly different backgrounds and takes on the world of marketing.</p>
<p>That variety means we listeners get tips on<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ai-in-marketing"> making AI work for marketing</a> one week, and the next we learn how to keep overtly salesy ‚Äúknobheads‚Äù out of our online community.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-market-movers.webp" alt="Best marketing podcasts - Market Movers Podcast" width="779" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93770 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-market-movers.webp 779w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-market-movers-480x370.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 779px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://marketmoverspod.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>‚ÄúWe‚Äôre broader than a lot of marketing shows,‚Äù Christopher explained. ‚ÄúWe don‚Äôt stick to a narrow niche. We cover a wide range of topics and invite a variety of guests. A lot of them we‚Äôve actually met in person, often at conferences. Having that prior connection really breaks down the third wall and makes the conversations more open.‚Äù</p>
<p>That open exchange of ideas that happens when professionals meet is exactly the vibe Christopher and Nick curate on their show. ‚ÄúWe were doing a lot of networking at conferences and kept meeting interesting people with great stories and insights,‚Äù Christopher said. ‚ÄúYou pick up so many useful tidbits at conferences that it almost feels like a waste not to share them.‚Äù</p>
<p>My favorite part of Market Movers is the enthusiasm Nick and Christopher bring to learning right along with the audience. ‚ÄúWe don‚Äôt pretend to know everything, and we‚Äôre genuinely curious,‚Äù Christopher said. ‚ÄúWhen a guest talks about something we don‚Äôt fully understand, we‚Äôre not afraid to ask more questions and dig deeper.‚Äù</p>
<h4>One big takeaway</h4>
<p>If you find yourself stuck in the planning phase of projects for too long, you‚Äôre not alone. Running the Market Movers podcast has helped Christopher get past his analysis paralysis.</p>
<p>‚ÄúOne of the biggest mindset shifts I‚Äôve had is that you just have to test things and get them out there,‚Äù Michael said. ‚ÄúYou can plan forever, but real value comes from launching and learning in real-time. Whether it‚Äôs a new funnel, an <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/lead-nurturing-emails">email sequence</a>, or anything else, it‚Äôs better to put it live, get feedback, and make changes on the fly.‚Äù</p>
<p>‚ÄúSome of the best results I‚Äôve seen have come from launching something that flopped, tweaking it, relaunching it, and eventually figuring out what worked and why,‚Äù he continued. ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs been the biggest shift for me, to stop waiting for perfect. Just launch, learn, and refine.‚Äù</p>
<h4>The past episode to have in your playlist</h4>
<p>‚ÄúPersonally, the solo <a href="https://www.marketmoverspod.com/e/the-7-figure-deal-tim-stoddart-s-risky-bet-on-copyblogger/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">interview I did with Tim Stoddart</a> really stuck with me,‚Äù Christopher said. ‚ÄúHis story is powerful. He‚Äôs overcome a lot and achieved a huge amount, and I think he‚Äôs in a really good place now. That episode definitely resonated with me, and I‚Äôd recommend giving it a listen.‚Äù</p>
<div id="the-market-mindset-podcast"></div>
<h3>3. The Marketing Mindset Podcast</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/colby-flood/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Colby Flood</a> prioritizes an ‚ÄúEducation First‚Äù philosophy at his agency,<a href="https://www.brighterclick.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> BrighterClick</a>. That mantra drives<a href="https://www.brighterclick.com/marketing-mindset-podcast" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> The Marketing Mindset</a>‚Äîa podcast that gets in the weeds of ground-level marketing with people who live and breathe it every day.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-marketing-mindset.webp" alt="Best marketing podcasts - Marketing Mindset" width="835" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93771 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-marketing-mindset.webp 835w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-marketing-mindset-480x345.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 835px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLfney7s8PpE8dHdI296ujqFIDv4Z4ydlO" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>‚ÄúWhat I think sets Marketing Mindset apart is the intent behind it,‚Äù Colby said. ‚ÄúEverything we share is driven by a single priority, which is helping people grow and learn, both personally and in their business. That means keeping the content transparent, trustworthy, and free from hidden agendas.‚Äù</p>
<p>I love how they dig deep into a specific topic in each episode. Look over the list and you‚Äôll see titles like ‚ÄúHow to start <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/tiktok-marketing-for-small-businesses/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">selling on TikTok</a> Shops‚Äù and ‚ÄúCreating a Facebook Ads Creative Report Template.‚Äù There‚Äôs even a seven-part series dedicated to building a high-level creative strategy process.</p>
<p>‚ÄúMy vision for the podcast has evolved from being a place to communicate with people already well-known in the industry, to also finding the people working in the weeds to have them share their expertise, and help build their personal brands,‚Äù Colby said.</p>
<p>‚ÄúOur goal is simple,‚Äù he added. ‚ÄúKeep the main priority the main priority, which is delivering honest, actionable insights that help people succeed.‚Äù</p>
<h4>One big takeaway</h4>
<p>I‚Äôm guilty of reading a marketing success story and forgetting all the background context that led to the result. Colby said that getting the full story from his guests reminds him of all the turbulence that happens before a smooth landing.</p>
<p>‚ÄúOne of the most refreshing things I have learned from hosting the show is that a lot of growth lessons come in hindsight,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúYes, there are people who can plan and execute exactly as intended, but more often the real breakthroughs are understood retrospectively.‚Äù</p>
<p>‚ÄúOn social media, it can seem like every success story was the result of a flawless plan,‚Äù Colby explained. ‚ÄúPeople share how they did X, Y, or Z, and it led to a big win, and it can give the impression that it was all intentional from the start. In reality, many of those wins become clear only when you look back and analyze what actually drove the results.‚Äù</p>
<p>‚ÄúThrough my own experience and countless guest conversations, I have realized the value of post-implementation reviews. Taking the time to reflect on what truly worked and why can turn everyday actions into long-term growth lessons.‚Äù</p>
<h4>The past episode to have in your playlist</h4>
<p>‚ÄúOne episode that really stands out to me was my <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tI9jscqQ1Qo" target="_blank" rel="noopener">interview with Ben</a>, the CEO of True Classic,‚Äù Colby shared. ‚ÄúBefore that conversation, I was a meticulous planner. I would map out the year, then the quarter, then the month, break that into weeks, and even down to daily tasks. Planning has value, but Ben really shifted my perspective on execution.‚Äù</p>
<p>‚ÄúHe emphasized the importance of focusing on what needs to be done today or this week, especially in a fast-moving business. Things change so quickly that planning too far ahead can sometimes work against you, particularly in a startup.‚Äù</p>
<p>‚ÄúLooking back, I think my heavy focus on planning was a bit of a defense mechanism to avoid failure. But real growth comes from failing fast, learning quickly, and pivoting when needed. That episode helped me embrace the idea of spending less time perfecting a plan and more time acting on it.‚Äù</p>
<div id="the-marketing-chatroom"></div>
<h3>4. The Marketing Chatroom</h3>
<p>If you‚Äôre looking for a little fresh air in the sometimes stuffy confines of digital marketing, I highly recommend giving <a href="https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL9cBWyQM0Rb4_eMtKTsSPxBD1eOnYy0go" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Marketing Chatroom</a> a listen. Host <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/kayla-bryant-sacramento/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Kayla Bryant</a>, general manager of <a href="https://twotreesppc.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Two Trees PPC</a>, brings a vibe that she describes as ‚Äúupbeat, slightly silly, and that should feel like you‚Äôre talking to a friend.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-marketing-chatroom.webp" alt="Best marketing podcasts - The Marketing Chatroom" width="814" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93772 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-marketing-chatroom.webp 814w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-marketing-chatroom-480x354.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 814px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL9cBWyQM0Rb4_eMtKTsSPxBD1eOnYy0go" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>‚ÄúBased on what I hear from guests and listeners, my podcast is more approachable and casual,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúI talk with marketers about their real challenges and unique approaches toward success in their careers.‚Äù</p>
<p>Kayla and her guests get into the tactical side of marketing often, but the best bits for me are the episodes that explore soft‚Äîbut critical‚Äî<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/04/07/marketing-skills">marketing skills</a> like empathy and creativity. It‚Äôs interesting to learn how people in the field put those ideas into practice.</p>
<p>‚ÄúI thought it would be cool to have a platform to highlight insights from marketing professionals in a variety of industries, roles, and places in their careers,‚Äù she said. ‚ÄúI&#8217;ve learned that as a host, I don&#8217;t have to be perfect or have a formal plan or specific questions prepared. As long as I have a guest with a story to tell and a general episode theme in mind- being open to a genuine conversation about something the guest is passionate about or expert at produces the best results.‚Äù</p>
<h4>One big takeaway</h4>
<p>Remote work has plenty of benefits, but sometimes it can feel a little isolating. Kayla said that listening to her guests confirms that a collaborative attitude is still critical for marketing success.</p>
<p>‚ÄúAcross the board, through my conversations, I&#8217;ve noticed that the most successful marketers (in my opinion) are those who have a true team mindset,‚Äù she explained. ‚ÄúThey&#8217;ve become leaders in the space because they rise by lifting up others. They all started in the trenches doing the work, but they&#8217;ve found opportunities to improve upon their own work and taught others along the way. They aren&#8217;t afraid to share their knowledge alongside their challenges.‚Äù</p>
<h4>The past episode to have in your playlist</h4>
<p>‚ÄúI struggle to not label every episode as my favorite, because each one is so interesting and unique,‚Äù Kayla told me. Fair enough, I‚Äôm not sure I can pick favorites from my work, either.</p>
<p>But if I were picking a place to start in the Marketing Chatroom, I‚Äôd say the<a href="https://youtu.be/mAZfQrUynoM?si=_wF4S936V0mkCJnp" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> chat with David Young</a> on the power of storytelling. Storytelling has become almost clich√© these days, but David does a great job of grounding it in results.</p>
<div id="fm"></div>
<h3>5. Plugin.fm</h3>
<p>Where many podcasts cover marketing broadly across every industry,<a href="http://plugin.fm" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> Plugin.fm</a> stays narrow and deep by helping practitioners build a software business to navigate various growth challenges.</p>
<p>‚ÄúMost marketing podcasts are marketers talking to other marketers,‚Äù said <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/goranmirkovic/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Goran Mirkovic</a>, the chief marketing officer at <a href="https://freemius.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Freemius</a>, who co-hosts the show with Patrick Rauland. ‚ÄúOurs is different because it speaks directly to indie software makers and encourages them to take bigger swings with their products.‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-pluginfm.webp" alt="Best marketing podcasts - Plugin.fm" width="937" height="608" class="aligncenter wp-image-93773 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-pluginfm.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-pluginfm-480x311.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="http://plugin.fm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Source</a></em></p>
<p>Originally, the show was a great way for the Freemius folks to learn about their <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/customer-pain-points/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">target audience‚Äôs struggles</a> and to build relationships with industry leaders. ‚ÄúThe podcast gave us a reason to sit down with them for an hour and ask the questions we genuinely cared about,‚Äù Goran said.</p>
<p>As they compiled more episodes, though, Goran said they noticed the library had a different purpose. ‚Äú[It became] more about co-creating useful resources with industry experts for indie founders and small software teams who don‚Äôt have mentors or investors guiding them. What began as a learning tool has grown into a library of practical stories and strategies from real builders.‚Äù</p>
<p>While marketing is a core component of the show‚Äôs topics, it also seeks to solve other hurdles like pricing experiments, subscription headaches, and customer support struggles.‚ÄúThese are the challenges that actually keep small teams up at night,‚Äù Goran said. ‚ÄúOur goal is to inspire and educate, not to sell.‚Äù</p>
<h4>One big takeaway</h4>
<p>Software startups can get caught up in the race to grow fast. So can we marketers. Goran said the conversations on Plugin.fm have reminded him that having a strong foundation is more important than growing sky-high too fast.</p>
<p>‚ÄúStop chasing ‚Äòscale‚Äô too early,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúA lot of our guests reinforced the idea that you don‚Äôt need 10,000 customers. What you need is 50 loyal ones who give feedback, renew, and tell others about you. That shift in mindset is freeing. Instead of obsessing over growth hacks, focus on building something so useful that a small group sticks with you. Scale comes later if you get that right.‚Äù</p>
<h4>The past episode to have in your playlist</h4>
<p>As a content marketer who‚Äôs always riding the tumultuous waves of SEO, Goran‚Äôs pick for one of his favorite episodes of Plugin.fm hit home for me.</p>
<p>‚ÄúOne that really stood out was our <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e2zgI2b6q44" target="_blank" rel="noopener">conversation with Rand Fishkin</a>,‚Äù Goran said. ‚ÄúHe‚Äôs someone everyone associates with SEO, yet he told us that SparkToro gets fewer than 50 visits a month from Google. This is a guy whose work has been cited in Congress and even by the US president, but <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/08/03/organic-traffic">organic search</a> barely moves the needle for his business. That hit our audience hard because it showed how much the game has changed and why you <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-marketing-pros-drive-traffic">can‚Äôt rely only on Google for growth</a>.‚Äù</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f44b.png" alt="üëã" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Free resource!</strong> <a href="https://marketing.localiq.com/WSLIQContentDL25LeadGenIdeas.html?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_LeadGenIdeas_Download">The Definitive Guide to Lead Generation: 25 Ideas (+Tips &amp; Examples)</a></p>
<div id="3-more-marketing-podcasts"></div>
<h2>3 more marketing podcasts for your learning pleasure</h2>
<p>I got so many great recommendations for this list that I couldn‚Äôt expand on all of them. Here are a handful of additional marketing podcasts worthy of your next long drive.</p>
<div id="content-briefly"></div>
<h3>6. Content, Briefly</h3>
<p><a href="https://podcast.superpath.co/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Content, Briefly</a> is one of my personal favorite marketing podcasts, so I was glad when another marketer suggested it. It‚Äôs a weekly interview show that focuses on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/07/13/content-marketing-strategy">content marketing</a>.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcast-wordstream-content-briefly.webp" alt="best marketing podcasts - Content, Briefly" width="702" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93784 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcast-wordstream-content-briefly.webp 702w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcast-wordstream-content-briefly-480x410.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 702px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://podcast.superpath.co/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Source</a></p>
<p>What I like about this one is that hosts Jimmy Daly and Eric Doty ask guests about the specific tactics and tools they use to do their jobs. So while there‚Äôs plenty of friendly chatting to enjoy, you also get some specific takeaways to apply.</p>
<div id="the-artificial-intelligence-show"></div>
<h3>7. The Artificial Intelligence Show</h3>
<p>For good and bad, AI is an absolute wrecking ball in<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ai-marketing-trends-2025"> marketing</a>. There are a few things it hasn‚Äôt changed significantly. That‚Äôs why I‚Äôm so grateful that hosts Paul Roetzer and Mike Kaput tackle these tumultuous topics in<a href="https://www.marketingaiinstitute.com/podcast-showcase" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> The Artificial Intelligence Show</a>.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcast-wordstream-artificial-intelligence-show.webp" alt="best marketing podcasts - The Artificial Intelligence Show" width="937" height="391" class="aligncenter wp-image-93785 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcast-wordstream-artificial-intelligence-show.webp 937w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcast-wordstream-artificial-intelligence-show-480x200.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 937px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.marketingaiinstitute.com/podcast-showcase" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Source</em></a></p>
<p>The show breaks down AI news, with a strong bent towards how it affects marketing. Even though it‚Äôs a current events format, there is a lot of actionable information you can use. For example, Paul and Mike often discuss the impacts of new AI tech that is useful in marketing.</p>
<div id="breaking-b2b"></div>
<h3>8. Breaking B2B</h3>
<p>I was lucky enough to gather some of<a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/samdunning/?originalSubdomain=uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> Sam Dunning‚Äôs</a> wisdom in a past post on<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/seo-trends-2025"> SEO trends</a>. His<a href="https://www.breakingb2b.com/blog" target="_blank" rel="noopener"> Breaking B2B podcast</a> is a torrent of tactics and teardowns for technical SEOs, content marketers, and marketing generalists who need to drive more traffic from search engines.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-breaking-b2b.webp" alt="best marketing podcasts - Breaking B2B " width="853" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-93786 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-breaking-b2b.webp 853w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/best-marketing-podcasts-wordstream-breaking-b2b-480x338.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 853px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://www.breakingb2b.com/blog" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Source</a></em></p>
<p>Much of Sam‚Äôs content is geared towards B2B and SaaS SEO. But you can definitely glean loads of useful information, no matter what type of website you‚Äôre trying to rank.</p>
<h2>The best marketing podcasts in 2025</h2>
<p>I can‚Äôt say which podcast is best, but I can say which podcasts I think you should prioritize. It‚Äôs the ones that talk about the challenges you have. Scroll through their playlists, look up a few of the guests, and read some of the intros. You‚Äôll get a sense of what they cover.</p>
<p>I also highly recommend reaching out to the podcasters. Ask about their show, share ideas, and suggest guests. We‚Äôre all communicators trying to make a connection, after all.</p>
